⏺ A/B bays — high value, clear mechanic. Two named slots, SAVE STATE writes to
  active bay, toggle loads it. Replaces the disk. Ship it.

  Undo/Redo — depends what it operates on. Two options:

  - Intake params (lens, floor, horizon, magnitude, rules, shock toggle) — this
  is the right scope. You're building a query, mis-click a chip, hit undo.
  Simple history stack, cheap to implement, genuinely useful mid-query. This is
  what FabFilter does — per-parameter granularity.
  - Sessions (full execute states) — murkier. You already have the replay system
  for frame history. Undo on a committed session means rolling back an
  arbitration + envelope, which is re-entering the intake state from a previous
  execute. Doable but heavier, and the bay system already covers the "go back to
  a saved state" use case.

  Recommendation: Undo/Redo scoped to intake params only. Before you hit
  execute, you can walk back any change you made to the form. Once you execute,
  that's a committed session — that's what the bays are for.

